                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d178">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Ambassador <persName type="to">Wright</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1906-08-31">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 31, 1906</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 27.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                    dispatch No. 37 of the 2d instant, inquiring whether the Japanese secretary of
                    your embassy is authorized to perform notarial acts under Revised Statutes,
                    1750.</p>
                <p>In reply, I have to inform you that the “Japanese secretary and interpreter to
                    embassy to Japan,” as he is officially designated, would not seem to be either a
                    secretary of legation or a consular officer within the meaning of Revised
                    Statutes, 1674, and is, therefore, apparently not empowered to act as a notary
                    under Revised Statutes, 1750, which authorizes “every secretary of legation and
                    consular officers” to perform any notarial act.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Alvey A. Adee</hi>,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
